        <link id="build-style-article" rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="/products/rsna/releasedAssets/css/build-article-8932601a697666afa607.css"/><article xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" data-design="pill" data-has="right-rail" data-type="research-article" vocab="http://schema.org/" typeof="ScholarlyArticle" lang="en" dir="ltr"><header data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><div data-article-access="no" data-article-access-type="other" class="meta-panel"><div class="meta-panel__left-content"><div class="meta-panel__label"><span>Cardiac Imaging</span></div><div class="meta-panel__onlineDate">Jul 1 2020</div></div><div class="meta-panel__right-content"><div class="meta-panel__share"></div></div></div><h1 property="name">Cardiac MRI in Pulmonary Hypertension: From Magnet to Bedside</h1><div class="contributors"><span class="authors"><span class="heading">Authors</span>: <span role="list"><span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con1"><span property="givenName">Jordi</span> <span property="familyName">Broncano</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a> <a class="orcid-id" href="https://orcid.org/0000-0002-0683-8061" property="identifier" aria-label="ORCID identifier" target="_blank">https://orcid.org/0000-0002-0683-8061</a> <a href="/cdn-cgi/l/email-protection#96fcb8f4e4f9f8f5f7f8f9b8f5d6fee2fffbf3b8f9e4f1" property="email" aria-label="Email address"><span class="__cf_email__" data-cfemail="1973377b6b76777a787776377a59716d70747c37766b7e">[email&#160;protected]</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con2"><span property="givenName">Sanjeev</span> <span property="familyName">Bhalla</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a> <a class="orcid-id" href="https://orcid.org/0000-0002-1262-8925" property="identifier" aria-label="ORCID identifier" target="_blank">https://orcid.org/0000-0002-1262-8925</a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con3"><span property="givenName">Fernando R.</span> <span property="familyName">Gutierrez</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con4"><span property="givenName">Daniel</span> <span property="familyName">Vargas</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a> <a class="orcid-id" href="https://orcid.org/0000-0001-8207-4609" property="identifier" aria-label="ORCID identifier" target="_blank">https://orcid.org/0000-0001-8207-4609</a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con5"><span property="givenName">Eric E.</span> <span property="familyName">Williamson</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con6"><span property="givenName">Majesh</span> <span property="familyName">Makan</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a></span>, and <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con7"><span property="givenName">Antonio</span> <span property="familyName">Luna</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD, PhD</span></a> <a class="orcid-id" href="https://orcid.org/0000-0001-9358-3396" property="identifier" aria-label="ORCID identifier" target="_blank">https://orcid.org/0000-0001-9358-3396</a></span></span></span><a href="#tab-contributors" class="to-authors-affiliations" data-id="article-authors-viewall">Authors Info &amp; Affiliations</a></div><div class="core-self-citation"><div property="isPartOf" typeof="Periodical"><span class="heading">Publication</span>: <span property="name">RadioGraphics</span></div><div class="core-enumeration"><span property="isPartOf" typeof="PublicationVolume">Volume <span property="volumeNumber">40</span></span><span class="delimiter">, </span><span property="isPartOf" typeof="PublicationIssue">Number <span property="issueNumber">4</span></span></div><div class="doi"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1148/rg.2020190179" property="sameAs">https://doi.org/10.1148/rg.2020190179</a></div></div><div class="info-panel"><div class="info-panel__left-content"><div class="info-panel__metrics info-panel__item"></div></div><div class="info-panel__right-content"><div class="info-panel__article_tools info-panel__item">



        
        <div class="article-tools"><a href="/personalize/addFavoritePublication?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179" target="_blank" class="article-tools__favorite btn btn--slim btn--inverse" data-toggle="tooltip" data-trigger="hover" data-original-title="Add to favorites"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-add-favorite"></i><span class="sr-only">Add to favorites</span></a><a href="/action/addCitationAlert?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179" target="_blank" class="article-tools__citation btn btn--slim btn--inverse" data-toggle="tooltip" data-trigger="hover" data-original-title="Track Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-alert-bell"></i><span class="sr-only">Track Citations</span></a></div>
</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Pulmonary hypertension (PH) is a disease characterized by progressive rise of pulmonary artery (PA) pressure, which can lead to right ventricular (RV) failure. It is usually diagnosed late because of the nonspecificity of its symptoms. RV performance and adaptation to an increased afterload, reflecting the interaction of the PA and RV as a morphofunctional unit, constitute a critical determinant of morbidity and mortality in these patients. Therefore, early detection of dysfunction may prevent treatment failure. Cardiac MRI constitutes one of the most complete diagnostic modalities for diagnosing PH. It allows evaluation of the morphology and hemodynamics of the PA and RV. Several cine steady-state free-precession (SSFP)–derived parameters (indexed RV end-diastolic volume or RV systolic volume) and phase-contrast regional area change have been suggested as powerful biomarkers for prognosis and treatment. Recently, new cardiac MRI sequences have been added to clinical protocols for PH evaluation, providing brand-new information. Strain analysis with myocardial feature tracking can help detect early RV dysfunction, even with preserved ejection fraction. Four-dimensional flow cardiac MRI can enhance assessment of advanced RV and PA hemodynamics. Late gadolinium enhancement (LGE) imaging may allow detection of replacement fibrosis in PH patients, which is associated with poor outcome. T1 mapping may help detect interstitial fibrosis, even with normal LGE imaging results. The authors analyze the imaging workup of PH with a focus on the role of morphologic and functional cardiac MRI in diagnosis and management of PH, including some of the newer techniques.</div><div role="paragraph"><i>Online supplemental material is available for this article.</i></div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2020</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2020190179">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2020190179">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic" aria-label="Different forms of PH and corresponding hemodynamic characteristics. CO = cardiac output, CTEPH = chronic thromboembolic PH, mPAP = mean PA pressure, PAH = idiopathic PA hypertension, PCWP = pulmonary capillary wedge pressure, PVR = pulmonary venous resistance, TPG = transpulmonary gradient, WHO = World Health Organization, WU = Wood units."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190179/asset/images/large/rg.2020190179.fig1.jpeg" height="2154" width="3800" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. Different forms of PH and corresponding hemodynamic characteristics. <i>CO</i> = cardiac output, <i>CTEPH</i> = chronic thromboembolic PH, <i>mPAP</i> = mean PA pressure, <i>PAH</i> = idiopathic PA hypertension, <i>PCWP</i> = pulmonary capillary wedge pressure, <i>PVR</i> = pulmonary venous resistance, <i>TPG</i> = transpulmonary gradient, <i>WHO</i> = World Health Organization, WU = Wood units.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic" aria-label="Physiopathology of PH. The two main factors responsible for PH are increased pulmonary vascular resistance (PVR) and elevated pulmonary venous pressure (PVP). PVR can be caused by obliteration of the pulmonary vascular bed or hypoxic vasoconstriction. PH is characterized by pulmonary vessel wall remodeling, vasoconstriction, and smooth vessel hypertrophy. Pulmonary vessel wall remodeling in PH is due to thickening of the media and to plexiform lesions involving muscular arterioles and pulmonary venules but also to muscularization of nonmuscular arterioles. The thickening of the media is composed of hypertrophy and hyperplasia of endothelial cells (ECs), fibroblasts, and smooth muscle cells (SMCs). By contrast, a plexiform lesion is secondary to proliferation and disorganization of monoclonal endothelial cells and altered myofibroblastic stroma. Muscularization refers to extension of new smooth muscle into partially muscular and nonmuscular peripheral arterioles. This vascular remodeling leads to increased PA stiffness. As a result, a low-gradient low-pressure system develops, increasing PA stiffness and RV afterload. When this elevated afterload is chronic, the RV initially adapts by increasing its wall thickness (RV hypertrophy), thus maintaining the cardiac output (asymptomatic compensated state). Owing to a disbalance between the oxygen supply and demand of a hypertrophied RV, a compromise in its pump function may develop (symptomatic decompensating state). As a result of heterogeneous remodeling, RV dilatation occurs, increasing ventricular wall stress and flattening of the interventricular septum (interventricular septal bowing [ISB]). Enlargement of the tricuspid annulus, which leads to tricuspid regurgitation, increased size of the right atrium and inferior vena cava, and impairment of LV function may reflect advanced features of PH (advanced decompensating state)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190179/asset/images/large/rg.2020190179.fig2.jpeg" height="1891" width="3795" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. Physiopathology of PH. The two main factors responsible for PH are increased pulmonary vascular resistance (PVR) and elevated pulmonary venous pressure (PVP). PVR can be caused by obliteration of the pulmonary vascular bed or hypoxic vasoconstriction. PH is characterized by pulmonary vessel wall remodeling, vasoconstriction, and smooth vessel hypertrophy. Pulmonary vessel wall remodeling in PH is due to thickening of the media and to plexiform lesions involving muscular arterioles and pulmonary venules but also to muscularization of nonmuscular arterioles. The thickening of the media is composed of hypertrophy and hyperplasia of endothelial cells <i>(ECs)</i>, fibroblasts, and smooth muscle cells <i>(SMCs)</i>. By contrast, a plexiform lesion is secondary to proliferation and disorganization of monoclonal endothelial cells and altered myofibroblastic stroma. Muscularization refers to extension of new smooth muscle into partially muscular and nonmuscular peripheral arterioles. This vascular remodeling leads to increased PA stiffness. As a result, a low-gradient low-pressure system develops, increasing PA stiffness and RV afterload. When this elevated afterload is chronic, the RV initially adapts by increasing its wall thickness (RV hypertrophy), thus maintaining the cardiac output (asymptomatic compensated state). Owing to a disbalance between the oxygen supply and demand of a hypertrophied RV, a compromise in its pump function may develop (symptomatic decompensating state). As a result of heterogeneous remodeling, RV dilatation occurs, increasing ventricular wall stress and flattening of the interventricular septum (interventricular septal bowing <i>[ISB]</i>). Enlargement of the tricuspid annulus, which leads to tricuspid regurgitation, increased size of the right atrium and inferior vena cava, and impairment of LV function may reflect advanced features of PH (advanced decompensating state).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic" aria-label="PFA and PH. T1-weighted double inversion-recovery black-blood turbo spin-echo images in four patients with PH show dilatation of the PA without PFA (a), with PFA in the distal right PA (arrow in b), with PFA in the proximal right PA (arrow in c), and with PFA in the main PA (arrow in d). Note that the more proximal the PFA is, the worse prognosis the patient would have."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190179/asset/images/large/rg.2020190179.fig3a.jpeg" height="1383" width="1378" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. PFA and PH. T1-weighted double inversion-recovery black-blood turbo spin-echo images in four patients with PH show dilatation of the PA without PFA <b>(a)</b>, with PFA in the distal right PA (arrow in <b>b</b>), with PFA in the proximal right PA (arrow in <b>c</b>), and with PFA in the main PA (arrow in <b>d</b>). Note that the more proximal the PFA is, the worse prognosis the patient would have.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic" aria-label="PFA and PH. T1-weighted double inversion-recovery black-blood turbo spin-echo images in four patients with PH show dilatation of the PA without PFA (a), with PFA in the distal right PA (arrow in b), with PFA in the proximal right PA (arrow in c), and with PFA in the main PA (arrow in d). Note that the more proximal the PFA is, the worse prognosis the patient would have."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190179/asset/images/large/rg.2020190179.fig3b.jpeg" height="1383" width="1272" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. PFA and PH. T1-weighted double inversion-recovery black-blood turbo spin-echo images in four patients with PH show dilatation of the PA without PFA <b>(a)</b>, with PFA in the distal right PA (arrow in <b>b</b>), with PFA in the proximal right PA (arrow in <b>c</b>), and with PFA in the main PA (arrow in <b>d</b>). Note that the more proximal the PFA is, the worse prognosis the patient would have.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic" aria-label="PFA and PH. T1-weighted double inversion-recovery black-blood turbo spin-echo images in four patients with PH show dilatation of the PA without PFA (a), with PFA in the distal right PA (arrow in b), with PFA in the proximal right PA (arrow in c), and with PFA in the main PA (arrow in d). Note that the more proximal the PFA is, the worse prognosis the patient would have."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190179/asset/images/large/rg.2020190179.fig3c.jpeg" height="1304" width="1336" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span>. PFA and PH. T1-weighted double inversion-recovery black-blood turbo spin-echo images in four patients with PH show dilatation of the PA without PFA <b>(a)</b>, with PFA in the distal right PA (arrow in <b>b</b>), with PFA in the proximal right PA (arrow in <b>c</b>), and with PFA in the main PA (arrow in <b>d</b>). Note that the more proximal the PFA is, the worse prognosis the patient would have.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3d" class="graphic" aria-label="PFA and PH. T1-weighted double inversion-recovery black-blood turbo spin-echo images in four patients with PH show dilatation of the PA without PFA (a), with PFA in the distal right PA (arrow in b), with PFA in the proximal right PA (arrow in c), and with PFA in the main PA (arrow in d). Note that the more proximal the PFA is, the worse prognosis the patient would have."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190179/asset/images/large/rg.2020190179.fig3d.jpeg" height="1304" width="1314" aria-labelledby="fig3d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3d</span>. PFA and PH. T1-weighted double inversion-recovery black-blood turbo spin-echo images in four patients with PH show dilatation of the PA without PFA <b>(a)</b>, with PFA in the distal right PA (arrow in <b>b</b>), with PFA in the proximal right PA (arrow in <b>c</b>), and with PFA in the main PA (arrow in <b>d</b>). Note that the more proximal the PFA is, the worse prognosis the patient would have.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig3d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic" aria-label="Short-axis cine SSFP images of the basal segments of the heart. (a) SSFP image at end diastole shows extension of the basal lateral and inferior segments of the dilated RV proximal to the atrioventricular groove (red outline). (b) SSFP image at end systole does not show those segments seen at end diastole owing to longitudinal shortening of the RV. This comparison demonstrates the “shoulder” of the RV in a patient with PH."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190179/asset/images/large/rg.2020190179.fig4a.jpeg" height="1349" width="1350" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Short-axis cine SSFP images of the basal segments of the heart. <b>(a)</b> SSFP image at end diastole shows extension of the basal lateral and inferior segments of the dilated RV proximal to the atrioventricular groove (red outline). <b>(b)</b> SSFP image at end systole does not show those segments seen at end diastole owing to longitudinal shortening of the RV. This comparison demonstrates the “shoulder” of the RV in a patient with PH.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic" aria-label="Short-axis cine SSFP images of the basal segments of the heart. (a) SSFP image at end diastole shows extension of the basal lateral and inferior segments of the dilated RV proximal to the atrioventricular groove (red outline). (b) SSFP image at end systole does not show those segments seen at end diastole owing to longitudinal shortening of the RV. This comparison demonstrates the “shoulder” of the RV in a patient with PH."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190179/asset/images/large/rg.2020190179.fig4b.jpeg" height="1349" width="1297" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Short-axis cine SSFP images of the basal segments of the heart. <b>(a)</b> SSFP image at end diastole shows extension of the basal lateral and inferior segments of the dilated RV proximal to the atrioventricular groove (red outline). <b>(b)</b> SSFP image at end systole does not show those segments seen at end diastole owing to longitudinal shortening of the RV. This comparison demonstrates the “shoulder” of the RV in a patient with PH.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic" aria-label="Myocardial feature tracking (MFT) and myocardial strain. The optical flow postprocessing method is a block matching approach applied to a standard cine SSFP sequence. This block matching approach tracks subendocardial motion, including displacement and velocity, to infer myocardial deformation. Myocardial strain (MS) is the deformation produced by application of a force and represents the change in myocardial length from the relaxed state (L0) to the contractile state (L). This allows appreciation of different spatial components of contractile functions in the longitudinal (Long), circumferential (Circ), and radial (Rad) dimensions in systole and diastole. As a result, myocardial longitudinal strain, circumferential strain, and radial strain can be calculated."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190179/asset/images/large/rg.2020190179.fig5.jpeg" height="1580" width="2500" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span>. Myocardial feature tracking (MFT) and myocardial strain. The optical flow postprocessing method is a block matching approach applied to a standard cine SSFP sequence. This block matching approach tracks subendocardial motion, including displacement and velocity, to infer myocardial deformation. Myocardial strain <i>(MS)</i> is the deformation produced by application of a force and represents the change in myocardial length from the relaxed state <i>(L</i><sub><i>0</i></sub><i>)</i> to the contractile state <i>(L)</i>. This allows appreciation of different spatial components of contractile functions in the longitudinal <i>(Long)</i>, circumferential <i>(Circ)</i>, and radial <i>(Rad)</i> dimensions in systole and diastole. As a result, myocardial longitudinal strain, circumferential strain, and radial strain can be calculated.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic" aria-label="Strain analysis with MFT in a 47-year-old woman with idiopathic PA hypertension. (a) Short-axis cine SSFP image shows circumferential strain (CS) analysis of the RV. Note the higher values of CS in the free wall (white arrow) than in the anterior and inferior walls (black arrows). (b) Short-axis SSFP image shows a dilated and hypertrophied RV and interventricular septal bowing related to altered interventricular dependence. At CS analysis of the LV, there is increased CS of the septum (arrow), higher than that of the RV free wall. (c) On a short-axis SSFP image, radial strain (RS) analysis of the LV in the end-systolic phase shows reduced RS in the interventricular septum (arrow) compared with the rest of the LV segments. (d) Graph from American Heart Association segment-per-segment MFT RS analysis shows reduced RS of the septum (purple line) compared with the rest of the LV segments (blue lines)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190179/asset/images/large/rg.2020190179.fig6a.jpeg" height="1190" width="1564" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. Strain analysis with MFT in a 47-year-old woman with idiopathic PA hypertension. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis cine SSFP image shows circumferential strain (CS) analysis of the RV. Note the higher values of CS in the free wall (white arrow) than in the anterior and inferior walls (black arrows). <b>(b)</b> Short-axis SSFP image shows a dilated and hypertrophied RV and interventricular septal bowing related to altered interventricular dependence. At CS analysis of the LV, there is increased CS of the septum (arrow), higher than that of the RV free wall. <b>(c)</b> On a short-axis SSFP image, radial strain (RS) analysis of the LV in the end-systolic phase shows reduced RS in the interventricular septum (arrow) compared with the rest of the LV segments. <b>(d)</b> Graph from American Heart Association segment-per-segment MFT RS analysis shows reduced RS of the septum (purple line) compared with the rest of the LV segments (blue lines).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic" aria-label="Strain analysis with MFT in a 47-year-old woman with idiopathic PA hypertension. (a) Short-axis cine SSFP image shows circumferential strain (CS) analysis of the RV. Note the higher values of CS in the free wall (white arrow) than in the anterior and inferior walls (black arrows). (b) Short-axis SSFP image shows a dilated and hypertrophied RV and interventricular septal bowing related to altered interventricular dependence. At CS analysis of the LV, there is increased CS of the septum (arrow), higher than that of the RV free wall. (c) On a short-axis SSFP image, radial strain (RS) analysis of the LV in the end-systolic phase shows reduced RS in the interventricular septum (arrow) compared with the rest of the LV segments. (d) Graph from American Heart Association segment-per-segment MFT RS analysis shows reduced RS of the septum (purple line) compared with the rest of the LV segments (blue lines)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190179/asset/images/large/rg.2020190179.fig6b.jpeg" height="1190" width="1585" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. Strain analysis with MFT in a 47-year-old woman with idiopathic PA hypertension. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis cine SSFP image shows circumferential strain (CS) analysis of the RV. Note the higher values of CS in the free wall (white arrow) than in the anterior and inferior walls (black arrows). <b>(b)</b> Short-axis SSFP image shows a dilated and hypertrophied RV and interventricular septal bowing related to altered interventricular dependence. At CS analysis of the LV, there is increased CS of the septum (arrow), higher than that of the RV free wall. <b>(c)</b> On a short-axis SSFP image, radial strain (RS) analysis of the LV in the end-systolic phase shows reduced RS in the interventricular septum (arrow) compared with the rest of the LV segments. <b>(d)</b> Graph from American Heart Association segment-per-segment MFT RS analysis shows reduced RS of the septum (purple line) compared with the rest of the LV segments (blue lines).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic" aria-label="Strain analysis with MFT in a 47-year-old woman with idiopathic PA hypertension. (a) Short-axis cine SSFP image shows circumferential strain (CS) analysis of the RV. Note the higher values of CS in the free wall (white arrow) than in the anterior and inferior walls (black arrows). (b) Short-axis SSFP image shows a dilated and hypertrophied RV and interventricular septal bowing related to altered interventricular dependence. At CS analysis of the LV, there is increased CS of the septum (arrow), higher than that of the RV free wall. (c) On a short-axis SSFP image, radial strain (RS) analysis of the LV in the end-systolic phase shows reduced RS in the interventricular septum (arrow) compared with the rest of the LV segments. (d) Graph from American Heart Association segment-per-segment MFT RS analysis shows reduced RS of the septum (purple line) compared with the rest of the LV segments (blue lines)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190179/asset/images/large/rg.2020190179.fig6c.jpeg" height="1205" width="1595" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span>. Strain analysis with MFT in a 47-year-old woman with idiopathic PA hypertension. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis cine SSFP image shows circumferential strain (CS) analysis of the RV. Note the higher values of CS in the free wall (white arrow) than in the anterior and inferior walls (black arrows). <b>(b)</b> Short-axis SSFP image shows a dilated and hypertrophied RV and interventricular septal bowing related to altered interventricular dependence. At CS analysis of the LV, there is increased CS of the septum (arrow), higher than that of the RV free wall. <b>(c)</b> On a short-axis SSFP image, radial strain (RS) analysis of the LV in the end-systolic phase shows reduced RS in the interventricular septum (arrow) compared with the rest of the LV segments. <b>(d)</b> Graph from American Heart Association segment-per-segment MFT RS analysis shows reduced RS of the septum (purple line) compared with the rest of the LV segments (blue lines).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6d" class="graphic" aria-label="Strain analysis with MFT in a 47-year-old woman with idiopathic PA hypertension. (a) Short-axis cine SSFP image shows circumferential strain (CS) analysis of the RV. Note the higher values of CS in the free wall (white arrow) than in the anterior and inferior walls (black arrows). (b) Short-axis SSFP image shows a dilated and hypertrophied RV and interventricular septal bowing related to altered interventricular dependence. At CS analysis of the LV, there is increased CS of the septum (arrow), higher than that of the RV free wall. (c) On a short-axis SSFP image, radial strain (RS) analysis of the LV in the end-systolic phase shows reduced RS in the interventricular septum (arrow) compared with the rest of the LV segments. (d) Graph from American Heart Association segment-per-segment MFT RS analysis shows reduced RS of the septum (purple line) compared with the rest of the LV segments (blue lines)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190179/asset/images/large/rg.2020190179.fig6d.jpeg" height="1207" width="1555" aria-labelledby="fig6d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6d</span>. Strain analysis with MFT in a 47-year-old woman with idiopathic PA hypertension. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis cine SSFP image shows circumferential strain (CS) analysis of the RV. Note the higher values of CS in the free wall (white arrow) than in the anterior and inferior walls (black arrows). <b>(b)</b> Short-axis SSFP image shows a dilated and hypertrophied RV and interventricular septal bowing related to altered interventricular dependence. At CS analysis of the LV, there is increased CS of the septum (arrow), higher than that of the RV free wall. <b>(c)</b> On a short-axis SSFP image, radial strain (RS) analysis of the LV in the end-systolic phase shows reduced RS in the interventricular septum (arrow) compared with the rest of the LV segments. <b>(d)</b> Graph from American Heart Association segment-per-segment MFT RS analysis shows reduced RS of the septum (purple line) compared with the rest of the LV segments (blue lines).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig6d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic" aria-label="MR images in a 19-year-old woman with acute chest pain and acute bilateral pulmonary embolism. (a–c) Images from initial examination. (a) MR angiogram shows bilateral central filling defects (arrow) and a dilated main PA, consistent with acute pulmonary embolism. (b) Four-chamber cine SSFP image in diastole shows a dilated RV with presence of the “shoulder” of the RV (arrowhead) and flattening of the interventricular septum related to altered interventricular dependence (arrow). Note the dilated right atrium (*). (c) Four-chamber cine SSFP image shows tricuspid regurgitation secondary to RV dilatation (arrow). (d–f) Images from first follow-up after initiation of treatment. (d) MR angiogram shows significant reduction of the thrombus load, with an eccentric and smaller filling defect of the left PA (arrow). Reduction of the main PA diameter is consistent with subacute pulmonary embolism. (e, f) Four-chamber cine SSFP images at end diastole (e) and end systole (f) show significant reduction of RVEDV with absence of the shoulder of the RV, although it remains slightly dilated (* in e). There is minimal flattening of the interventricular septum at end diastole (e); this constitutes a feature of good prognosis. Note the reduction in size of the right atrium and the absence of tricuspid regurgitation (arrow in f). (g–i) Images from final follow-up after completion of acute pulmonary embolism treatment. (g) MR angiogram shows complete resolution of the pulmonary embolism with normal PA diameter. (h, i) Four-chamber cine SSFP images in diastole (h) and systole (i) show a normal RV with absence of tricuspid regurgitation, no enlarged right atrium, and normal interventricular dependence, consistent with a return to normality of a pressure-overloaded RV."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190179/asset/images/large/rg.2020190179.fig7a.jpeg" height="1122" width="1239" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. MR images in a 19-year-old woman with acute chest pain and acute bilateral pulmonary embolism. <b>(a–c)</b> Images from initial examination. <b>(a)</b> MR angiogram shows bilateral central filling defects (arrow) and a dilated main PA, consistent with acute pulmonary embolism. <b>(b)</b> Four-chamber cine SSFP image in diastole shows a dilated RV with presence of the “shoulder” of the RV (arrowhead) and flattening of the interventricular septum related to altered interventricular dependence (arrow). Note the dilated right atrium (*). <b>(c)</b> Four-chamber cine SSFP image shows tricuspid regurgitation secondary to RV dilatation (arrow). <b>(d–f)</b> Images from first follow-up after initiation of treatment. <b>(d)</b> MR angiogram shows significant reduction of the thrombus load, with an eccentric and smaller filling defect of the left PA (arrow). Reduction of the main PA diameter is consistent with subacute pulmonary embolism. <b>(e, f)</b> Four-chamber cine SSFP images at end diastole <b>(e)</b> and end systole <b>(f)</b> show significant reduction of RVEDV with absence of the shoulder of the RV, although it remains slightly dilated (* in <b>e</b>). There is minimal flattening of the interventricular septum at end diastole <b>(e)</b>; this constitutes a feature of good prognosis. Note the reduction in size of the right atrium and the absence of tricuspid regurgitation (arrow in <b>f</b>). <b>(g–i)</b> Images from final follow-up after completion of acute pulmonary embolism treatment. <b>(g)</b> MR angiogram shows complete resolution of the pulmonary embolism with normal PA diameter. <b>(h, i)</b> Four-chamber cine SSFP images in diastole <b>(h)</b> and systole <b>(i)</b> show a normal RV with absence of tricuspid regurgitation, no enlarged right atrium, and normal interventricular dependence, consistent with a return to normality of a pressure-overloaded RV.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic" aria-label="MR images in a 19-year-old woman with acute chest pain and acute bilateral pulmonary embolism. (a–c) Images from initial examination. (a) MR angiogram shows bilateral central filling defects (arrow) and a dilated main PA, consistent with acute pulmonary embolism. (b) Four-chamber cine SSFP image in diastole shows a dilated RV with presence of the “shoulder” of the RV (arrowhead) and flattening of the interventricular septum related to altered interventricular dependence (arrow). Note the dilated right atrium (*). (c) Four-chamber cine SSFP image shows tricuspid regurgitation secondary to RV dilatation (arrow). (d–f) Images from first follow-up after initiation of treatment. (d) MR angiogram shows significant reduction of the thrombus load, with an eccentric and smaller filling defect of the left PA (arrow). Reduction of the main PA diameter is consistent with subacute pulmonary embolism. (e, f) Four-chamber cine SSFP images at end diastole (e) and end systole (f) show significant reduction of RVEDV with absence of the shoulder of the RV, although it remains slightly dilated (* in e). There is minimal flattening of the interventricular septum at end diastole (e); this constitutes a feature of good prognosis. Note the reduction in size of the right atrium and the absence of tricuspid regurgitation (arrow in f). (g–i) Images from final follow-up after completion of acute pulmonary embolism treatment. (g) MR angiogram shows complete resolution of the pulmonary embolism with normal PA diameter. (h, i) Four-chamber cine SSFP images in diastole (h) and systole (i) show a normal RV with absence of tricuspid regurgitation, no enlarged right atrium, and normal interventricular dependence, consistent with a return to normality of a pressure-overloaded RV."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190179/asset/images/large/rg.2020190179.fig7b.jpeg" height="1122" width="1233" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. MR images in a 19-year-old woman with acute chest pain and acute bilateral pulmonary embolism. <b>(a–c)</b> Images from initial examination. <b>(a)</b> MR angiogram shows bilateral central filling defects (arrow) and a dilated main PA, consistent with acute pulmonary embolism. <b>(b)</b> Four-chamber cine SSFP image in diastole shows a dilated RV with presence of the “shoulder” of the RV (arrowhead) and flattening of the interventricular septum related to altered interventricular dependence (arrow). Note the dilated right atrium (*). <b>(c)</b> Four-chamber cine SSFP image shows tricuspid regurgitation secondary to RV dilatation (arrow). <b>(d–f)</b> Images from first follow-up after initiation of treatment. <b>(d)</b> MR angiogram shows significant reduction of the thrombus load, with an eccentric and smaller filling defect of the left PA (arrow). Reduction of the main PA diameter is consistent with subacute pulmonary embolism. <b>(e, f)</b> Four-chamber cine SSFP images at end diastole <b>(e)</b> and end systole <b>(f)</b> show significant reduction of RVEDV with absence of the shoulder of the RV, although it remains slightly dilated (* in <b>e</b>). There is minimal flattening of the interventricular septum at end diastole <b>(e)</b>; this constitutes a feature of good prognosis. Note the reduction in size of the right atrium and the absence of tricuspid regurgitation (arrow in <b>f</b>). <b>(g–i)</b> Images from final follow-up after completion of acute pulmonary embolism treatment. <b>(g)</b> MR angiogram shows complete resolution of the pulmonary embolism with normal PA diameter. <b>(h, i)</b> Four-chamber cine SSFP images in diastole <b>(h)</b> and systole <b>(i)</b> show a normal RV with absence of tricuspid regurgitation, no enlarged right atrium, and normal interventricular dependence, consistent with a return to normality of a pressure-overloaded RV.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7c" class="graphic" aria-label="MR images in a 19-year-old woman with acute chest pain and acute bilateral pulmonary embolism. (a–c) Images from initial examination. (a) MR angiogram shows bilateral central filling defects (arrow) and a dilated main PA, consistent with acute pulmonary embolism. (b) Four-chamber cine SSFP image in diastole shows a dilated RV with presence of the “shoulder” of the RV (arrowhead) and flattening of the interventricular septum related to altered interventricular dependence (arrow). Note the dilated right atrium (*). (c) Four-chamber cine SSFP image shows tricuspid regurgitation secondary to RV dilatation (arrow). (d–f) Images from first follow-up after initiation of treatment. (d) MR angiogram shows significant reduction of the thrombus load, with an eccentric and smaller filling defect of the left PA (arrow). Reduction of the main PA diameter is consistent with subacute pulmonary embolism. (e, f) Four-chamber cine SSFP images at end diastole (e) and end systole (f) show significant reduction of RVEDV with absence of the shoulder of the RV, although it remains slightly dilated (* in e). There is minimal flattening of the interventricular septum at end diastole (e); this constitutes a feature of good prognosis. Note the reduction in size of the right atrium and the absence of tricuspid regurgitation (arrow in f). (g–i) Images from final follow-up after completion of acute pulmonary embolism treatment. (g) MR angiogram shows complete resolution of the pulmonary embolism with normal PA diameter. (h, i) Four-chamber cine SSFP images in diastole (h) and systole (i) show a normal RV with absence of tricuspid regurgitation, no enlarged right atrium, and normal interventricular dependence, consistent with a return to normality of a pressure-overloaded RV."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190179/asset/images/large/rg.2020190179.fig7c.jpeg" height="1122" width="1226" aria-labelledby="fig7c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7c</span>. MR images in a 19-year-old woman with acute chest pain and acute bilateral pulmonary embolism. <b>(a–c)</b> Images from initial examination. <b>(a)</b> MR angiogram shows bilateral central filling defects (arrow) and a dilated main PA, consistent with acute pulmonary embolism. <b>(b)</b> Four-chamber cine SSFP image in diastole shows a dilated RV with presence of the “shoulder” of the RV (arrowhead) and flattening of the interventricular septum related to altered interventricular dependence (arrow). Note the dilated right atrium (*). <b>(c)</b> Four-chamber cine SSFP image shows tricuspid regurgitation secondary to RV dilatation (arrow). <b>(d–f)</b> Images from first follow-up after initiation of treatment. <b>(d)</b> MR angiogram shows significant reduction of the thrombus load, with an eccentric and smaller filling defect of the left PA (arrow). Reduction of the main PA diameter is consistent with subacute pulmonary embolism. <b>(e, f)</b> Four-chamber cine SSFP images at end diastole <b>(e)</b> and end systole <b>(f)</b> show significant reduction of RVEDV with absence of the shoulder of the RV, although it remains slightly dilated (* in <b>e</b>). There is minimal flattening of the interventricular septum at end diastole <b>(e)</b>; this constitutes a feature of good prognosis. Note the reduction in size of the right atrium and the absence of tricuspid regurgitation (arrow in <b>f</b>). <b>(g–i)</b> Images from final follow-up after completion of acute pulmonary embolism treatment. <b>(g)</b> MR angiogram shows complete resolution of the pulmonary embolism with normal PA diameter. <b>(h, i)</b> Four-chamber cine SSFP images in diastole <b>(h)</b> and systole <b>(i)</b> show a normal RV with absence of tricuspid regurgitation, no enlarged right atrium, and normal interventricular dependence, consistent with a return to normality of a pressure-overloaded RV.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig7c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7d" class="graphic" aria-label="MR images in a 19-year-old woman with acute chest pain and acute bilateral pulmonary embolism. (a–c) Images from initial examination. (a) MR angiogram shows bilateral central filling defects (arrow) and a dilated main PA, consistent with acute pulmonary embolism. (b) Four-chamber cine SSFP image in diastole shows a dilated RV with presence of the “shoulder” of the RV (arrowhead) and flattening of the interventricular septum related to altered interventricular dependence (arrow). Note the dilated right atrium (*). (c) Four-chamber cine SSFP image shows tricuspid regurgitation secondary to RV dilatation (arrow). (d–f) Images from first follow-up after initiation of treatment. (d) MR angiogram shows significant reduction of the thrombus load, with an eccentric and smaller filling defect of the left PA (arrow). Reduction of the main PA diameter is consistent with subacute pulmonary embolism. (e, f) Four-chamber cine SSFP images at end diastole (e) and end systole (f) show significant reduction of RVEDV with absence of the shoulder of the RV, although it remains slightly dilated (* in e). There is minimal flattening of the interventricular septum at end diastole (e); this constitutes a feature of good prognosis. Note the reduction in size of the right atrium and the absence of tricuspid regurgitation (arrow in f). (g–i) Images from final follow-up after completion of acute pulmonary embolism treatment. (g) MR angiogram shows complete resolution of the pulmonary embolism with normal PA diameter. (h, i) Four-chamber cine SSFP images in diastole (h) and systole (i) show a normal RV with absence of tricuspid regurgitation, no enlarged right atrium, and normal interventricular dependence, consistent with a return to normality of a pressure-overloaded RV."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190179/asset/images/large/rg.2020190179.fig7d.jpeg" height="1123" width="1226" aria-labelledby="fig7d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7d</span>. MR images in a 19-year-old woman with acute chest pain and acute bilateral pulmonary embolism. <b>(a–c)</b> Images from initial examination. <b>(a)</b> MR angiogram shows bilateral central filling defects (arrow) and a dilated main PA, consistent with acute pulmonary embolism. <b>(b)</b> Four-chamber cine SSFP image in diastole shows a dilated RV with presence of the “shoulder” of the RV (arrowhead) and flattening of the interventricular septum related to altered interventricular dependence (arrow). Note the dilated right atrium (*). <b>(c)</b> Four-chamber cine SSFP image shows tricuspid regurgitation secondary to RV dilatation (arrow). <b>(d–f)</b> Images from first follow-up after initiation of treatment. <b>(d)</b> MR angiogram shows significant reduction of the thrombus load, with an eccentric and smaller filling defect of the left PA (arrow). Reduction of the main PA diameter is consistent with subacute pulmonary embolism. <b>(e, f)</b> Four-chamber cine SSFP images at end diastole <b>(e)</b> and end systole <b>(f)</b> show significant reduction of RVEDV with absence of the shoulder of the RV, although it remains slightly dilated (* in <b>e</b>). There is minimal flattening of the interventricular septum at end diastole <b>(e)</b>; this constitutes a feature of good prognosis. Note the reduction in size of the right atrium and the absence of tricuspid regurgitation (arrow in <b>f</b>). <b>(g–i)</b> Images from final follow-up after completion of acute pulmonary embolism treatment. <b>(g)</b> MR angiogram shows complete resolution of the pulmonary embolism with normal PA diameter. <b>(h, i)</b> Four-chamber cine SSFP images in diastole <b>(h)</b> and systole <b>(i)</b> show a normal RV with absence of tricuspid regurgitation, no enlarged right atrium, and normal interventricular dependence, consistent with a return to normality of a pressure-overloaded RV.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig7d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7e" class="graphic" aria-label="MR images in a 19-year-old woman with acute chest pain and acute bilateral pulmonary embolism. (a–c) Images from initial examination. (a) MR angiogram shows bilateral central filling defects (arrow) and a dilated main PA, consistent with acute pulmonary embolism. (b) Four-chamber cine SSFP image in diastole shows a dilated RV with presence of the “shoulder” of the RV (arrowhead) and flattening of the interventricular septum related to altered interventricular dependence (arrow). Note the dilated right atrium (*). (c) Four-chamber cine SSFP image shows tricuspid regurgitation secondary to RV dilatation (arrow). (d–f) Images from first follow-up after initiation of treatment. (d) MR angiogram shows significant reduction of the thrombus load, with an eccentric and smaller filling defect of the left PA (arrow). Reduction of the main PA diameter is consistent with subacute pulmonary embolism. (e, f) Four-chamber cine SSFP images at end diastole (e) and end systole (f) show significant reduction of RVEDV with absence of the shoulder of the RV, although it remains slightly dilated (* in e). There is minimal flattening of the interventricular septum at end diastole (e); this constitutes a feature of good prognosis. Note the reduction in size of the right atrium and the absence of tricuspid regurgitation (arrow in f). (g–i) Images from final follow-up after completion of acute pulmonary embolism treatment. (g) MR angiogram shows complete resolution of the pulmonary embolism with normal PA diameter. (h, i) Four-chamber cine SSFP images in diastole (h) and systole (i) show a normal RV with absence of tricuspid regurgitation, no enlarged right atrium, and normal interventricular dependence, consistent with a return to normality of a pressure-overloaded RV."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190179/asset/images/large/rg.2020190179.fig7e.jpeg" height="1123" width="1230" aria-labelledby="fig7e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7e</span>. MR images in a 19-year-old woman with acute chest pain and acute bilateral pulmonary embolism. <b>(a–c)</b> Images from initial examination. <b>(a)</b> MR angiogram shows bilateral central filling defects (arrow) and a dilated main PA, consistent with acute pulmonary embolism. <b>(b)</b> Four-chamber cine SSFP image in diastole shows a dilated RV with presence of the “shoulder” of the RV (arrowhead) and flattening of the interventricular septum related to altered interventricular dependence (arrow). Note the dilated right atrium (*). <b>(c)</b> Four-chamber cine SSFP image shows tricuspid regurgitation secondary to RV dilatation (arrow). <b>(d–f)</b> Images from first follow-up after initiation of treatment. <b>(d)</b> MR angiogram shows significant reduction of the thrombus load, with an eccentric and smaller filling defect of the left PA (arrow). Reduction of the main PA diameter is consistent with subacute pulmonary embolism. <b>(e, f)</b> Four-chamber cine SSFP images at end diastole <b>(e)</b> and end systole <b>(f)</b> show significant reduction of RVEDV with absence of the shoulder of the RV, although it remains slightly dilated (* in <b>e</b>). There is minimal flattening of the interventricular septum at end diastole <b>(e)</b>; this constitutes a feature of good prognosis. Note the reduction in size of the right atrium and the absence of tricuspid regurgitation (arrow in <b>f</b>). <b>(g–i)</b> Images from final follow-up after completion of acute pulmonary embolism treatment. <b>(g)</b> MR angiogram shows complete resolution of the pulmonary embolism with normal PA diameter. <b>(h, i)</b> Four-chamber cine SSFP images in diastole <b>(h)</b> and systole <b>(i)</b> show a normal RV with absence of tricuspid regurgitation, no enlarged right atrium, and normal interventricular dependence, consistent with a return to normality of a pressure-overloaded RV.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig7e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7f" class="graphic" aria-label="MR images in a 19-year-old woman with acute chest pain and acute bilateral pulmonary embolism. (a–c) Images from initial examination. (a) MR angiogram shows bilateral central filling defects (arrow) and a dilated main PA, consistent with acute pulmonary embolism. (b) Four-chamber cine SSFP image in diastole shows a dilated RV with presence of the “shoulder” of the RV (arrowhead) and flattening of the interventricular septum related to altered interventricular dependence (arrow). Note the dilated right atrium (*). (c) Four-chamber cine SSFP image shows tricuspid regurgitation secondary to RV dilatation (arrow). (d–f) Images from first follow-up after initiation of treatment. (d) MR angiogram shows significant reduction of the thrombus load, with an eccentric and smaller filling defect of the left PA (arrow). Reduction of the main PA diameter is consistent with subacute pulmonary embolism. (e, f) Four-chamber cine SSFP images at end diastole (e) and end systole (f) show significant reduction of RVEDV with absence of the shoulder of the RV, although it remains slightly dilated (* in e). There is minimal flattening of the interventricular septum at end diastol