ng of the interventricular septum at end diastole <b>(e)</b>; this constitutes a feature of good prognosis. Note the reduction in size of the right atrium and the absence of tricuspid regurgitation (arrow in <b>f</b>). <b>(g–i)</b> Images from final follow-up after completion of acute pulmonary embolism treatment. <b>(g)</b> MR angiogram shows complete resolution of the pulmonary embolism with normal PA diameter. <b>(h, i)</b> Four-chamber cine SSFP images in diastole <b>(h)</b> and systole <b>(i)</b> show a normal RV with absence of tricuspid regurgitation, no enlarged right atrium, and normal interventricular dependence, consistent with a return to normality of a pressure-overloaded RV.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig7f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7g" class="graphic" aria-label="MR images in a 19-year-old woman with acute chest pain and acute bilateral pulmonary embolism. (a–c) Images from initial examination. (a) MR angiogram shows bilateral central filling defects (arrow) and a dilated main PA, consistent with acute pulmonary embolism. (b) Four-chamber cine SSFP image in diastole shows a dilated RV with presence of the “shoulder” of the RV (arrowhead) and flattening of the interventricular septum related to altered interventricular dependence (arrow). Note the dilated right atrium (*). (c) Four-chamber cine SSFP image shows tricuspid regurgitation secondary to RV dilatation (arrow). (d–f) Images from first follow-up after initiation of treatment. (d) MR angiogram shows significant reduction of the thrombus load, with an eccentric and smaller filling defect of the left PA (arrow). Reduction of the main PA diameter is consistent with subacute pulmonary embolism. (e, f) Four-chamber cine SSFP images at end diastole (e) and end systole (f) show significant reduction of RVEDV with absence of the shoulder of the RV, although it remains slightly dilated (* in e). There is minimal flattening of the interventricular septum at end diastole (e); this constitutes a feature of good prognosis. Note the reduction in size of the right atrium and the absence of tricuspid regurgitation (arrow in f). (g–i) Images from final follow-up after completion of acute pulmonary embolism treatment. (g) MR angiogram shows complete resolution of the pulmonary embolism with normal PA diameter. (h, i) Four-chamber cine SSFP images in diastole (h) and systole (i) show a normal RV with absence of tricuspid regurgitation, no enlarged right atrium, and normal interventricular dependence, consistent with a return to normality of a pressure-overloaded RV."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190179/asset/images/large/rg.2020190179.fig7g.jpeg" height="1127" width="1226" aria-labelledby="fig7g" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7g</span>. MR images in a 19-year-old woman with acute chest pain and acute bilateral pulmonary embolism. <b>(a–c)</b> Images from initial examination. <b>(a)</b> MR angiogram shows bilateral central filling defects (arrow) and a dilated main PA, consistent with acute pulmonary embolism. <b>(b)</b> Four-chamber cine SSFP image in diastole shows a dilated RV with presence of the “shoulder” of the RV (arrowhead) and flattening of the interventricular septum related to altered interventricular dependence (arrow). Note the dilated right atrium (*). <b>(c)</b> Four-chamber cine SSFP image shows tricuspid regurgitation secondary to RV dilatation (arrow). <b>(d–f)</b> Images from first follow-up after initiation of treatment. <b>(d)</b> MR angiogram shows significant reduction of the thrombus load, with an eccentric and smaller filling defect of the left PA (arrow). Reduction of the main PA diameter is consistent with subacute pulmonary embolism. <b>(e, f)</b> Four-chamber cine SSFP images at end diastole <b>(e)</b> and end systole <b>(f)</b> show significant reduction of RVEDV with absence of the shoulder of the RV, although it remains slightly dilated (* in <b>e</b>). There is minimal flattening of the interventricular septum at end diastole <b>(e)</b>; this constitutes a feature of good prognosis. Note the reduction in size of the right atrium and the absence of tricuspid regurgitation (arrow in <b>f</b>). <b>(g–i)</b> Images from final follow-up after completion of acute pulmonary embolism treatment. <b>(g)</b> MR angiogram shows complete resolution of the pulmonary embolism with normal PA diameter. <b>(h, i)</b> Four-chamber cine SSFP images in diastole <b>(h)</b> and systole <b>(i)</b> show a normal RV with absence of tricuspid regurgitation, no enlarged right atrium, and normal interventricular dependence, consistent with a return to normality of a pressure-overloaded RV.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig7g">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7h" class="graphic" aria-label="MR images in a 19-year-old woman with acute chest pain and acute bilateral pulmonary embolism. (a–c) Images from initial examination. (a) MR angiogram shows bilateral central filling defects (arrow) and a dilated main PA, consistent with acute pulmonary embolism. (b) Four-chamber cine SSFP image in diastole shows a dilated RV with presence of the “shoulder” of the RV (arrowhead) and flattening of the interventricular septum related to altered interventricular dependence (arrow). Note the dilated right atrium (*). (c) Four-chamber cine SSFP image shows tricuspid regurgitation secondary to RV dilatation (arrow). (d–f) Images from first follow-up after initiation of treatment. (d) MR angiogram shows significant reduction of the thrombus load, with an eccentric and smaller filling defect of the left PA (arrow). Reduction of the main PA diameter is consistent with subacute pulmonary embolism. (e, f) Four-chamber cine SSFP images at end diastole (e) and end systole (f) show significant reduction of RVEDV with absence of the shoulder of the RV, although it remains slightly dilated (* in e). There is minimal flattening of the interventricular septum at end diastole (e); this constitutes a feature of good prognosis. Note the reduction in size of the right atrium and the absence of tricuspid regurgitation (arrow in f). (g–i) Images from final follow-up after completion of acute pulmonary embolism treatment. (g) MR angiogram shows complete resolution of the pulmonary embolism with normal PA diameter. (h, i) Four-chamber cine SSFP images in diastole (h) and systole (i) show a normal RV with absence of tricuspid regurgitation, no enlarged right atrium, and normal interventricular dependence, consistent with a return to normality of a pressure-overloaded RV."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190179/asset/images/large/rg.2020190179.fig7h.jpeg" height="1127" width="1230" aria-labelledby="fig7h" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7h</span>. MR images in a 19-year-old woman with acute chest pain and acute bilateral pulmonary embolism. <b>(a–c)</b> Images from initial examination. <b>(a)</b> MR angiogram shows bilateral central filling defects (arrow) and a dilated main PA, consistent with acute pulmonary embolism. <b>(b)</b> Four-chamber cine SSFP image in diastole shows a dilated RV with presence of the “shoulder” of the RV (arrowhead) and flattening of the interventricular septum related to altered interventricular dependence (arrow). Note the dilated right atrium (*). <b>(c)</b> Four-chamber cine SSFP image shows tricuspid regurgitation secondary to RV dilatation (arrow). <b>(d–f)</b> Images from first follow-up after initiation of treatment. <b>(d)</b> MR angiogram shows significant reduction of the thrombus load, with an eccentric and smaller filling defect of the left PA (arrow). Reduction of the main PA diameter is consistent with subacute pulmonary embolism. <b>(e, f)</b> Four-chamber cine SSFP images at end diastole <b>(e)</b> and end systole <b>(f)</b> show significant reduction of RVEDV with absence of the shoulder of the RV, although it remains slightly dilated (* in <b>e</b>). There is minimal flattening of the interventricular septum at end diastole <b>(e)</b>; this constitutes a feature of good prognosis. Note the reduction in size of the right atrium and the absence of tricuspid regurgitation (arrow in <b>f</b>). <b>(g–i)</b> Images from final follow-up after completion of acute pulmonary embolism treatment. <b>(g)</b> MR angiogram shows complete resolution of the pulmonary embolism with normal PA diameter. <b>(h, i)</b> Four-chamber cine SSFP images in diastole <b>(h)</b> and systole <b>(i)</b> show a normal RV with absence of tricuspid regurgitation, no enlarged right atrium, and normal interventricular dependence, consistent with a return to normality of a pressure-overloaded RV.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig7h">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7i" class="graphic" aria-label="MR images in a 19-year-old woman with acute chest pain and acute bilateral pulmonary embolism. (a–c) Images from initial examination. (a) MR angiogram shows bilateral central filling defects (arrow) and a dilated main PA, consistent with acute pulmonary embolism. (b) Four-chamber cine SSFP image in diastole shows a dilated RV with presence of the “shoulder” of the RV (arrowhead) and flattening of the interventricular septum related to altered interventricular dependence (arrow). Note the dilated right atrium (*). (c) Four-chamber cine SSFP image shows tricuspid regurgitation secondary to RV dilatation (arrow). (d–f) Images from first follow-up after initiation of treatment. (d) MR angiogram shows significant reduction of the thrombus load, with an eccentric and smaller filling defect of the left PA (arrow). Reduction of the main PA diameter is consistent with subacute pulmonary embolism. (e, f) Four-chamber cine SSFP images at end diastole (e) and end systole (f) show significant reduction of RVEDV with absence of the shoulder of the RV, although it remains slightly dilated (* in e). There is minimal flattening of the interventricular septum at end diastole (e); this constitutes a feature of good prognosis. Note the reduction in size of the right atrium and the absence of tricuspid regurgitation (arrow in f). (g–i) Images from final follow-up after completion of acute pulmonary embolism treatment. (g) MR angiogram shows complete resolution of the pulmonary embolism with normal PA diameter. (h, i) Four-chamber cine SSFP images in diastole (h) and systole (i) show a normal RV with absence of tricuspid regurgitation, no enlarged right atrium, and normal interventricular dependence, consistent with a return to normality of a pressure-overloaded RV."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190179/asset/images/large/rg.2020190179.fig7i.jpeg" height="1127" width="1235" aria-labelledby="fig7i" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7i</span>. MR images in a 19-year-old woman with acute chest pain and acute bilateral pulmonary embolism. <b>(a–c)</b> Images from initial examination. <b>(a)</b> MR angiogram shows bilateral central filling defects (arrow) and a dilated main PA, consistent with acute pulmonary embolism. <b>(b)</b> Four-chamber cine SSFP image in diastole shows a dilated RV with presence of the “shoulder” of the RV (arrowhead) and flattening of the interventricular septum related to altered interventricular dependence (arrow). Note the dilated right atrium (*). <b>(c)</b> Four-chamber cine SSFP image shows tricuspid regurgitation secondary to RV dilatation (arrow). <b>(d–f)</b> Images from first follow-up after initiation of treatment. <b>(d)</b> MR angiogram shows significant reduction of the thrombus load, with an eccentric and smaller filling defect of the left PA (arrow). Reduction of the main PA diameter is consistent with subacute pulmonary embolism. <b>(e, f)</b> Four-chamber cine SSFP images at end diastole <b>(e)</b> and end systole <b>(f)</b> show significant reduction of RVEDV with absence of the shoulder of the RV, although it remains slightly dilated (* in <b>e</b>). There is minimal flattening of the interventricular septum at end diastole <b>(e)</b>; this constitutes a feature of good prognosis. Note the reduction in size of the right atrium and the absence of tricuspid regurgitation (arrow in <b>f</b>). <b>(g–i)</b> Images from final follow-up after completion of acute pulmonary embolism treatment. <b>(g)</b> MR angiogram shows complete resolution of the pulmonary embolism with normal PA diameter. <b>(h, i)</b> Four-chamber cine SSFP images in diastole <b>(h)</b> and systole <b>(i)</b> show a normal RV with absence of tricuspid regurgitation, no enlarged right atrium, and normal interventricular dependence, consistent with a return to normality of a pressure-overloaded RV.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig7i">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic" aria-label="Images from basal and control MFT examination in a 19-year-old woman with acute chest pain and acute bilateral pulmonary embolism (same patient as in Fig 7). (a–c) Images from MFT in the acute setting. (a) Image from two-dimensional circumferential strain (CS) analysis shows altered CS of the RV free wall (arrow). Note the enlargement of the RV with altered curvature of the interventricular septum, consistent with abnormal interventricular dependence. (b) Image from two-dimensional LV CS analysis shows altered CS (arrow) in the interventricular septum, which is flattened in relation to RV postsystolic contraction. The abnormal LV CS is higher than the altered RV CS at the free wall. (c) Image from three-dimensional CS analysis shows alteration of LV CS at the septum as well as abnormal interventricular dependence (arrow). (d–f) Images from MFT analysis after completion of treatment. (d) Image from two-dimensional CS analysis shows a normal-sized RV with improvement of CS at the free wall (arrow). Note the normal curvature of the interventricular septum. (e) Image from two-dimensional CS analysis shows improvement of LV CS at the septum with normal configuration (arrow). (f) Image from three-dimensional CS analysis shows resolution of the altered LV CS at the septum (arrow), which was secondary to RV overload due to acute pulmonary embolism. These evolving changes in the RV (reduced RVEDV), interventricular septum, and LV are consistent with a good prognosis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190179/asset/images/large/rg.2020190179.fig8a.jpeg" height="1042" width="1284" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. Images from basal and control MFT examination in a 19-year-old woman with acute chest pain and acute bilateral pulmonary embolism (same patient as in <a href="#fig7a">Fig 7</a>). <b>(a–c)</b> Images from MFT in the acute setting. <b>(a)</b> Image from two-dimensional circumferential strain (CS) analysis shows altered CS of the RV free wall (arrow). Note the enlargement of the RV with altered curvature of the interventricular septum, consistent with abnormal interventricular dependence. <b>(b)</b> Image from two-dimensional LV CS analysis shows altered CS (arrow) in the interventricular septum, which is flattened in relation to RV postsystolic contraction. The abnormal LV CS is higher than the altered RV CS at the free wall. <b>(c)</b> Image from three-dimensional CS analysis shows alteration of LV CS at the septum as well as abnormal interventricular dependence (arrow). <b>(d–f)</b> Images from MFT analysis after completion of treatment. <b>(d)</b> Image from two-dimensional CS analysis shows a normal-sized RV with improvement of CS at the free wall (arrow). Note the normal curvature of the interventricular septum. <b>(e)</b> Image from two-dimensional CS analysis shows improvement of LV CS at the septum with normal configuration (arrow). <b>(f)</b> Image from three-dimensional CS analysis shows resolution of the altered LV CS at the septum (arrow), which was secondary to RV overload due to acute pulmonary embolism. These evolving changes in the RV (reduced RVEDV), interventricular septum, and LV are consistent with a good prognosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic" aria-label="Images from basal and control MFT examination in a 19-year-old woman with acute chest pain and acute bilateral pulmonary embolism (same patient as in Fig 7). (a–c) Images from MFT in the acute setting. (a) Image from two-dimensional circumferential strain (CS) analysis shows altered CS of the RV free wall (arrow). Note the enlargement of the RV with altered curvature of the interventricular septum, consistent with abnormal interventricular dependence. (b) Image from two-dimensional LV CS analysis shows altered CS (arrow) in the interventricular septum, which is flattened in relation to RV postsystolic contraction. The abnormal LV CS is higher than the altered RV CS at the free wall. (c) Image from three-dimensional CS analysis shows alteration of LV CS at the septum as well as abnormal interventricular dependence (arrow). (d–f) Images from MFT analysis after completion of treatment. (d) Image from two-dimensional CS analysis shows a normal-sized RV with improvement of CS at the free wall (arrow). Note the normal curvature of the interventricular septum. (e) Image from two-dimensional CS analysis shows improvement of LV CS at the septum with normal configuration (arrow). (f) Image from three-dimensional CS analysis shows resolution of the altered LV CS at the septum (arrow), which was secondary to RV overload due to acute pulmonary embolism. These evolving changes in the RV (reduced RVEDV), interventricular septum, and LV are consistent with a good prognosis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190179/asset/images/large/rg.2020190179.fig8b.jpeg" height="1042" width="1286" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. Images from basal and control MFT examination in a 19-year-old woman with acute chest pain and acute bilateral pulmonary embolism (same patient as in <a href="#fig7a">Fig 7</a>). <b>(a–c)</b> Images from MFT in the acute setting. <b>(a)</b> Image from two-dimensional circumferential strain (CS) analysis shows altered CS of the RV free wall (arrow). Note the enlargement of the RV with altered curvature of the interventricular septum, consistent with abnormal interventricular dependence. <b>(b)</b> Image from two-dimensional LV CS analysis shows altered CS (arrow) in the interventricular septum, which is flattened in relation to RV postsystolic contraction. The abnormal LV CS is higher than the altered RV CS at the free wall. <b>(c)</b> Image from three-dimensional CS analysis shows alteration of LV CS at the septum as well as abnormal interventricular dependence (arrow). <b>(d–f)</b> Images from MFT analysis after completion of treatment. <b>(d)</b> Image from two-dimensional CS analysis shows a normal-sized RV with improvement of CS at the free wall (arrow). Note the normal curvature of the interventricular septum. <b>(e)</b> Image from two-dimensional CS analysis shows improvement of LV CS at the septum with normal configuration (arrow). <b>(f)</b> Image from three-dimensional CS analysis shows resolution of the altered LV CS at the septum (arrow), which was secondary to RV overload due to acute pulmonary embolism. These evolving changes in the RV (reduced RVEDV), interventricular septum, and LV are consistent with a good prognosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8c" class="graphic" aria-label="Images from basal and control MFT examination in a 19-year-old woman with acute chest pain and acute bilateral pulmonary embolism (same patient as in Fig 7). (a–c) Images from MFT in the acute setting. (a) Image from two-dimensional circumferential strain (CS) analysis shows altered CS of the RV free wall (arrow). Note the enlargement of the RV with altered curvature of the interventricular septum, consistent with abnormal interventricular dependence. (b) Image from two-dimensional LV CS analysis shows altered CS (arrow) in the interventricular septum, which is flattened in relation to RV postsystolic contraction. The abnormal LV CS is higher than the altered RV CS at the free wall. (c) Image from three-dimensional CS analysis shows alteration of LV CS at the septum as well as abnormal interventricular dependence (arrow). (d–f) Images from MFT analysis after completion of treatment. (d) Image from two-dimensional CS analysis shows a normal-sized RV with improvement of CS at the free wall (arrow). Note the normal curvature of the interventricular septum. (e) Image from two-dimensional CS analysis shows improvement of LV CS at the septum with normal configuration (arrow). (f) Image from three-dimensional CS analysis shows resolution of the altered LV CS at the septum (arrow), which was secondary to RV overload due to acute pulmonary embolism. These evolving changes in the RV (reduced RVEDV), interventricular septum, and LV are consistent with a good prognosis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190179/asset/images/large/rg.2020190179.fig8c.jpeg" height="1042" width="1128" aria-labelledby="fig8c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8c</span>. Images from basal and control MFT examination in a 19-year-old woman with acute chest pain and acute bilateral pulmonary embolism (same patient as in <a href="#fig7a">Fig 7</a>). <b>(a–c)</b> Images from MFT in the acute setting. <b>(a)</b> Image from two-dimensional circumferential strain (CS) analysis shows altered CS of the RV free wall (arrow). Note the enlargement of the RV with altered curvature of the interventricular septum, consistent with abnormal interventricular dependence. <b>(b)</b> Image from two-dimensional LV CS analysis shows altered CS (arrow) in the interventricular septum, which is flattened in relation to RV postsystolic contraction. The abnormal LV CS is higher than the altered RV CS at the free wall. <b>(c)</b> Image from three-dimensional CS analysis shows alteration of LV CS at the septum as well as abnormal interventricular dependence (arrow). <b>(d–f)</b> Images from MFT analysis after completion of treatment. <b>(d)</b> Image from two-dimensional CS analysis shows a normal-sized RV with improvement of CS at the free wall (arrow). Note the normal curvature of the interventricular septum. <b>(e)</b> Image from two-dimensional CS analysis shows improvement of LV CS at the septum with normal configuration (arrow). <b>(f)</b> Image from three-dimensional CS analysis shows resolution of the altered LV CS at the septum (arrow), which was secondary to RV overload due to acute pulmonary embolism. These evolving changes in the RV (reduced RVEDV), interventricular septum, and LV are consistent with a good prognosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig8c">Download as PowerPoint</a