e RV with altered curvature of the interventricular septum, consistent with abnormal interventricular dependence. (b) Image from two-dimensional LV CS analysis shows altered CS (arrow) in the interventricular septum, which is flattened in relation to RV postsystolic contraction. The abnormal LV CS is higher than the altered RV CS at the free wall. (c) Image from three-dimensional CS analysis shows alteration of LV CS at the septum as well as abnormal interventricular dependence (arrow). (d–f) Images from MFT analysis after completion of treatment. (d) Image from two-dimensional CS analysis shows a normal-sized RV with improvement of CS at the free wall (arrow). Note the normal curvature of the interventricular septum. (e) Image from two-dimensional CS analysis shows improvement of LV CS at the septum with normal configuration (arrow). (f) Image from three-dimensional CS analysis shows resolution of the altered LV CS at the septum (arrow), which was secondary to RV overload due to acute pulmonary embolism. These evolving changes in the RV (reduced RVEDV), interventricular septum, and LV are consistent with a good prognosis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190179/asset/images/large/rg.2020190179.fig8e.jpeg" height="1036" width="1281" aria-labelledby="fig8e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8e</span>. Images from basal and control MFT examination in a 19-year-old woman with acute chest pain and acute bilateral pulmonary embolism (same patient as in <a href="#fig7a">Fig 7</a>). <b>(a–c)</b> Images from MFT in the acute setting. <b>(a)</b> Image from two-dimensional circumferential strain (CS) analysis shows altered CS of the RV free wall (arrow). Note the enlargement of the RV with altered curvature of the interventricular septum, consistent with abnormal interventricular dependence. <b>(b)</b> Image from two-dimensional LV CS analysis shows altered CS (arrow) in the interventricular septum, which is flattened in relation to RV postsystolic contraction. The abnormal LV CS is higher than the altered RV CS at the free wall. <b>(c)</b> Image from three-dimensional CS analysis shows alteration of LV CS at the septum as well as abnormal interventricular dependence (arrow). <b>(d–f)</b> Images from MFT analysis after completion of treatment. <b>(d)</b> Image from two-dimensional CS analysis shows a normal-sized RV with improvement of CS at the free wall (arrow). Note the normal curvature of the interventricular septum. <b>(e)</b> Image from two-dimensional CS analysis shows improvement of LV CS at the septum with normal configuration (arrow). <b>(f)</b> Image from three-dimensional CS analysis shows resolution of the altered LV CS at the septum (arrow), which was secondary to RV overload due to acute pulmonary embolism. These evolving changes in the RV (reduced RVEDV), interventricular septum, and LV are consistent with a good prognosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig8e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8f" class="graphic" aria-label="Images from basal and control MFT examination in a 19-year-old woman with acute chest pain and acute bilateral pulmonary embolism (same patient as in Fig 7). (a–c) Images from MFT in the acute setting. (a) Image from two-dimensional circumferential strain (CS) analysis shows altered CS of the RV free wall (arrow). Note the enlargement of the RV with altered curvature of the interventricular septum, consistent with abnormal interventricular dependence. (b) Image from two-dimensional LV CS analysis shows altered CS (arrow) in the interventricular septum, which is flattened in relation to RV postsystolic contraction. The abnormal LV CS is higher than the altered RV CS at the free wall. (c) Image from three-dimensional CS analysis shows alteration of LV CS at the septum as well as abnormal interventricular dependence (arrow). (d–f) Images from MFT analysis after completion of treatment. (d) Image from two-dimensional CS analysis shows a normal-sized RV with improvement of CS at the free wall (arrow). Note the normal curvature of the interventricular septum. (e) Image from two-dimensional CS analysis shows improvement of LV CS at the septum with normal configuration (arrow). (f) Image from three-dimensional CS analysis shows resolution of the altered LV CS at the septum (arrow), which was secondary to RV overload due to acute pulmonary embolism. These evolving changes in the RV (reduced RVEDV), interventricular septum, and LV are consistent with a good prognosis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190179/asset/images/large/rg.2020190179.fig8f.jpeg" height="1036" width="1134" aria-labelledby="fig8f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8f</span>. Images from basal and control MFT examination in a 19-year-old woman with acute chest pain and acute bilateral pulmonary embolism (same patient as in <a href="#fig7a">Fig 7</a>). <b>(a–c)</b> Images from MFT in the acute setting. <b>(a)</b> Image from two-dimensional circumferential strain (CS) analysis shows altered CS of the RV free wall (arrow). Note the enlargement of the RV with altered curvature of the interventricular septum, consistent with abnormal interventricular dependence. <b>(b)</b> Image from two-dimensional LV CS analysis shows altered CS (arrow) in the interventricular septum, which is flattened in relation to RV postsystolic contraction. The abnormal LV CS is higher than the altered RV CS at the free wall. <b>(c)</b> Image from three-dimensional CS analysis shows alteration of LV CS at the septum as well as abnormal interventricular dependence (arrow). <b>(d–f)</b> Images from MFT analysis after completion of treatment. <b>(d)</b> Image from two-dimensional CS analysis shows a normal-sized RV with improvement of CS at the free wall (arrow). Note the normal curvature of the interventricular septum. <b>(e)</b> Image from two-dimensional CS analysis shows improvement of LV CS at the septum with normal configuration (arrow). <b>(f)</b> Image from three-dimensional CS analysis shows resolution of the altered LV CS at the septum (arrow), which was secondary to RV overload due to acute pulmonary embolism. These evolving changes in the RV (reduced RVEDV), interventricular septum, and LV are consistent with a good prognosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig8f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic" aria-label="Techniques for obtaining pulse wave velocity (PWV) of the PA. (a) Two-dimensional phase-contrast through-plane imaging using multiple breath holds at the main PA and right and left PA branches. (b) Four-dimensional flow cardiac MRI with retrospective selection of appropriate imaging planes at the main PA and right and left PA branches."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190179/asset/images/large/rg.2020190179.fig9a.jpeg" height="1471" width="1860" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Techniques for obtaining pulse wave velocity (PWV) of the PA. <b>(a)</b> Two-dimensional phase-contrast through-plane imaging using multiple breath holds at the main PA and right and left PA branches. <b>(b)</b> Four-dimensional flow cardiac MRI with retrospective selection of appropriate imaging planes at the main PA and right and left PA branches.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic" aria-label="Techniques for obtaining pulse wave velocity (PWV) of the PA. (a) Two-dimensional phase-contrast through-plane imaging using multiple breath holds at the main PA and right and left PA branches. (b) Four-dimensional flow cardiac MRI with retrospective selection of appropriate imaging planes at the main PA and right and left PA branches."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190179/asset/images/large/rg.2020190179.fig9b.jpeg" height="1471" width="1891" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Techniques for obtaining pulse wave velocity (PWV) of the PA. <b>(a)</b> Two-dimensional phase-contrast through-plane imaging using multiple breath holds at the main PA and right and left PA branches. <b>(b)</b> Four-dimensional flow cardiac MRI with retrospective selection of appropriate imaging planes at the main PA and right and left PA branches.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic" aria-label="Four-dimensional flow cardiac MRI–derived representations. (a) Instantaneous streamlines reflect the directions of flow through a cavity or vessel. They do not correspond to any path traveled by any blood cell. (b) Three-dimensional velocity vector maps display the magnitude and direction of blood flow velocity in each voxel. (c) Pathlines follow the path of theoretic virtual massless particles."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190179/asset/images/large/rg.2020190179.fig10a.jpeg" height="1173" width="1246" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. Four-dimensional flow cardiac MRI–derived representations. <b>(a)</b> Instantaneous streamlines reflect the directions of flow through a cavity or vessel. They do not correspond to any path traveled by any blood cell. <b>(b)</b> Three-dimensional velocity vector maps display the magnitude and direction of blood flow velocity in each voxel. <b>(c)</b> Pathlines follow the path of theoretic virtual massless particles.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic" aria-label="Four-dimensional flow cardiac MRI–derived representations. (a) Instantaneous streamlines reflect the directions of flow through a cavity or vessel. They do not correspond to any path traveled by any blood cell. (b) Three-dimensional velocity vector maps display the magnitude and direction of blood flow velocity in each voxel. (c) Pathlines follow the path of theoretic virtual massless particles."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190179/asset/images/large/rg.2020190179.fig10b.jpeg" height="1173" width="1238" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. Four-dimensional flow cardiac MRI–derived representations. <b>(a)</b> Instantaneous streamlines reflect the directions of flow through a cavity or vessel. They do not correspond to any path traveled by any blood cell. <b>(b)</b> Three-dimensional velocity vector maps display the magnitude and direction of blood flow velocity in each voxel. <b>(c)</b> Pathlines follow the path of theoretic virtual massless particles.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10c" class="graphic" aria-label="Four-dimensional flow cardiac MRI–derived representations. (a) Instantaneous streamlines reflect the directions of flow through a cavity or vessel. They do not correspond to any path traveled by any blood cell. (b) Three-dimensional velocity vector maps display the magnitude and direction of blood flow velocity in each voxel. (c) Pathlines follow the path of theoretic virtual massless particles."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190179/asset/images/large/rg.2020190179.fig10c.jpeg" height="1173" width="1216" aria-labelledby="fig10c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span>. Four-dimensional flow cardiac MRI–derived representations. <b>(a)</b> Instantaneous streamlines reflect the directions of flow through a cavity or vessel. They do not correspond to any path traveled by any blood cell. <b>(b)</b> Three-dimensional velocity vector maps display the magnitude and direction of blood flow velocity in each voxel. <b>(c)</b> Pathlines follow the path of theoretic virtual massless particles.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig10c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic" aria-label="Ostium secundum type 1 atrial septal defect (pulmonary flow [Qp] to systemic flow [Qs] ratio = 3.88:1) and type 1 PH in a 26-year-old woman with PA dilatation (33 mm; PA-to-aorta ratio &gt;1) due to RV overload. (a) Four-dimensional flow streamline image shows vortical flow in both PAs but mainly in the right PA (arrow). (b) Four-dimensional flow image shows altered and increased wall shear stress (WSS) (arrow) in the proximal segment of the right PA. (c) Four-dimensional flow image shows altered turbulent kinetic energy (TKE) (arrow) in the right PA."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190179/asset/images/large/rg.2020190179.fig11a.jpeg" height="1209" width="1257" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Ostium secundum type 1 atrial septal defect (pulmonary flow [<i>Q</i>p] to systemic flow [<i>Q</i>s] ratio = 3.88:1) and type 1 PH in a 26-year-old woman with PA dilatation (33 mm; PA-to-aorta ratio &gt;1) due to RV overload. <b>(a)</b> Four-dimensional flow streamline image shows vortical flow in both PAs but mainly in the right PA (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Four-dimensional flow image shows altered and increased wall shear stress (WSS) (arrow) in the proximal segment of the right PA. <b>(c)</b> Four-dimensional flow image shows altered turbulent kinetic energy (TKE) (arrow) in the right PA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic" aria-label="Ostium secundum type 1 atrial septal defect (pulmonary flow [Qp] to systemic flow [Qs] ratio = 3.88:1) and type 1 PH in a 26-year-old woman with PA dilatation (33 mm; PA-to-aorta ratio &gt;1) due to RV overload. (a) Four-dimensional flow streamline image shows vortical flow in both PAs but mainly in the right PA (arrow). (b) Four-dimensional flow image shows altered and increased wall shear stress (WSS) (arrow) in the proximal segment of the right PA. (c) Four-dimensional flow image shows altered turbulent kinetic energy (TKE) (arrow) in the right PA."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190179/asset/images/large/rg.2020190179.fig11b.jpeg" height="1209" width="1114" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. Ostium secundum type 1 atrial septal defect (pulmonary flow [<i>Q</i>p] to systemic flow [<i>Q</i>s] ratio = 3.88:1) and type 1 PH in a 26-year-old woman with PA dilatation (33 mm; PA-to-aorta ratio &gt;1) due to RV overload. <b>(a)</b> Four-dimensional flow streamline image shows vortical flow in both PAs but mainly in the right PA (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Four-dimensional flow image shows altered and increased wall shear stress (WSS) (arrow) in the proximal segment of the right PA. <b>(c)</b> Four-dimensional flow image shows altered turbulent kinetic energy (TKE) (arrow) in the right PA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11c" class="graphic" aria-label="Ostium secundum type 1 atrial septal defect (pulmonary flow [Qp] to systemic flow [Qs] ratio = 3.88:1) and type 1 PH in a 26-year-old woman with PA dilatation (33 mm; PA-to-aorta ratio &gt;1) due to RV overload. (a) Four-dimensional flow streamline image shows vortical flow in both PAs but mainly in the right PA (arrow). (b) Four-dimensional flow image shows altered and increased wall shear stress (WSS) (arrow) in the proximal segment of the right PA. (c) Four-dimensional flow image shows altered turbulent kinetic energy (TKE) (arrow) in the right PA."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190179/asset/images/large/rg.2020190179.fig11c.jpeg" height="1209" width="1329" aria-labelledby="fig11c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span>. Ostium secundum type 1 atrial septal defect (pulmonary flow [<i>Q</i>p] to systemic flow [<i>Q</i>s] ratio = 3.88:1) and type 1 PH in a 26-year-old woman with PA dilatation (33 mm; PA-to-aorta ratio &gt;1) due to RV overload. <b>(a)</b> Four-dimensional flow streamline image shows vortical flow in both PAs but mainly in the right PA (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Four-dimensional flow image shows altered and increased wall shear stress (WSS) (arrow) in the proximal segment of the right PA. <b>(c)</b> Four-dimensional flow image shows altered turbulent kinetic energy (TKE) (arrow) in the right PA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig11c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic" aria-label="Value of pulmonary transit time (PTT) derived from postcontrast first-pass perfusion imaging. Arrow = pulmonary peak time, arrowhead = systemic peak time. (a) Short-axis first-pass perfusion image in a healthy volunteer shows a normal PTT (5.7 seconds), which is considered nonaltered if it is less than 6 seconds. The difference between the pulmonary and systemic peak times corresponds to the PTT. (b) Short-axis first-pass perfusion image in a 45-year-old man with type 2 PH secondary to ischemic LV dilated myocardiopathy shows altered PTT (10.7 seconds) for passage of the contrast material bolus between the RV and LV."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190179/asset/images/large/rg.2020190179.fig12a.jpeg" height="1416" width="1875" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. Value of pulmonary transit time (PTT) derived from postcontrast first-pass perfusion imaging. Arrow = pulmonary peak time, arrowhead = systemic peak time. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis first-pass perfusion image in a healthy volunteer shows a normal PTT (5.7 seconds), which is considered nonaltered if it is less than 6 seconds. The difference between the pulmonary and systemic peak times corresponds to the PTT. <b>(b)</b> Short-axis first-pass perfusion image in a 45-year-old man with type 2 PH secondary to ischemic LV dilated myocardiopathy shows altered PTT (10.7 seconds) for passage of the contrast material bolus between the RV and LV.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic" aria-label="Value of pulmonary transit time (PTT) derived from postcontrast first-pass perfusion imaging. Arrow = pulmonary peak time, arrowhead = systemic peak time. (a) Short-axis first-pass perfusion image in a healthy volunteer shows a normal PTT (5.7 seconds), which is considered nonaltered if it is less than 6 seconds. The difference between the pulmonary and systemic peak times corresponds to the PTT. (b) Short-axis first-pass perfusion image in a 45-year-old man with type 2 PH secondary to ischemic LV dilated myocardiopathy shows altered PTT (10.7 seconds) for passage of the contrast material bolus between the RV and LV."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190179/asset/images/large/rg.2020190179.fig12b.jpeg" height="1416" width="1875" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. Value of pulmonary transit time (PTT) derived from postcontrast first-pass perfusion imaging. Arrow = pulmonary peak time, arrowhead = systemic peak time. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis first-pass perfusion image in a healthy volunteer shows a normal PTT (5.7 seconds), which is considered nonaltered if it is less than 6 seconds. The difference between the pulmonary and systemic peak times corresponds to the PTT. <b>(b)</b> Short-axis first-pass perfusion image in a 45-year-old man with type 2 PH secondary to ischemic LV dilated myocardiopathy shows altered PTT (10.7 seconds) for passage of the contrast material bolus between the RV and LV.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic" aria-label="Ostium secundum type 1 atrial septal defect and derived decompensated PH in a 26-year-old woman with RV enlargement and dysfunction with the reverse Bernheim effect. (a) Midventricular short-axis LGE image shows enhancement at the posterior septal insertion (arrow). (b, c) Midventricular short-axis native (b) and contrast-enhanced (c) T1 maps show alteration of native and postcontrast T1 mapping at the posterior septal insertion (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190179/asset/images/large/rg.2020190179.fig13a.jpeg" height="957" width="1248" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. Ostium secundum type 1 atrial septal defect and derived decompensated PH in a 26-year-old woman with RV enlargement and dysfunction with the reverse Bernheim effect. <b>(a)</b> Midventricular short-axis LGE image shows enhancement at the posterior septal insertion (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Midventricular short-axis native <b>(b)</b> and contrast-enhanced <b>(c)</b> T1 maps show alteration of native and postcontrast T1 mapping at the posterior septal insertion (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic" aria-label="Ostium secundum type 1 atrial septal defect and derived decompensated PH in a 26-year-old woman with RV enlargement and dysfunction with the reverse Bernheim effect. (a) Midventricular short-axis LGE image shows enhancement at the posterior septal insertion (arrow). (b, c) Midventricular short-axis native (b) and contrast-enhanced (c) T1 maps show alteration of native and postcontrast T1 mapping at the posterior septal insertion (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190179/asset/images/large/rg.2020190179.fig13b.jpeg" height="957" width="1204" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. Ostium secundum type 1 atrial septal defect and derived decompensated PH in a 26-year-old woman with RV enlargement and dysfunction with the reverse Bernheim effect. <b>(a)</b> Midventricular short-axis LGE image shows enhancement at the posterior septal insertion (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Midventricular short-axis native <b>(b)</b> and contrast-enhanced <b>(c)</b> T1 maps show alteration of native and postcontrast T1 mapping at the posterior septal insertion (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13c" class="graphic" aria-label="Ostium secundum type 1 atrial septal defect and derived decompensated PH in a 26-year-old woman with RV enlargement and dysfunction with the reverse Bernheim effect. (a) Midventricular short-axis LGE image shows enhancement at the posterior septal insertion (arrow). (b, c) Midventricular short-axis native (b) and contrast-enhanced (c) T1 maps show alteration of native and postcontrast T1 mapping at the posterior septal insertion (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190179/asset/images/large/rg.2020190179.fig13c.jpeg" height="957" width="1242" aria-labelledby="fig13c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13c</span>. Ostium secundum type 1 atrial septal defect and derived decompensated PH in a 26-year-old woman with RV enlargement and dysfunction with the reverse Bernheim effect. <b>(a)</b> Midventricular short-axis LGE image shows enhancement at the posterior septal insertion (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Midventricular short-axis native <b>(b)</b> and contrast-enhanced <b>(c)</b> T1 maps show alteration of native and postcontrast T1 mapping at the posterior septal insertion (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190179&amp;id=fig13c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Schiebl